description.text:
OK, have you ever wondered why Philips Sonicare toothbrushes come only with the same four cheesy "colors" as their marker rings?

Clips are slightly asymmetric and have their smaller side on top to adjust to the tooth brush form.

The "clip storage thing" in the last photo is another one of my designs.
You can download it here: Ring Object Storage - Dispenser

BTW: This is my 20th design that I uploaded to Thingiverse.

It may look like I'm a bit obsessed with Philips devices, especially with their Sonicare/Sensonic electric toothbrush line; and in fact I like their product(s) - a lot.
However, think about it: If the company would do an even better job designing their stuff in a more thoughtful way, I wouldn't have to pimp it like I do!!

remixed_from.title: Balloon Boat V3 UPDATE! - Compatible with Mini Figures

description.text:
Simple, quick and easy to print, parametric (you can change the sizes) - this is a nozzle to go in the mouth of a balloon. When you inflate the balloon and let it go, the nozzle controls the rate at which air is released from the balloon, which you can then adjust for maximum flight time, or altitude, or just for fun.

The .scad design includes fins, and I printed a few with fins, but they're not practical at all when it comes to filling the balloon with air, and I didn't see any improved flight characteristics. I did notice that a heavier (more infill) nozzle seems to increase stability, keeping the balloon more upright for more controlled flight.

For 12" latex balloons, I found that about 3.5mm openings were good for long flight times, much smaller and the weaker balloons don't make enough thrust to fly.

Jet propulsion

The balloon contains pressurized air, the nozzle releases the air at a controlled rate - this released air creates thrust. Newton's 3rd law: the air jetting out the nozzle pushes the balloon in the opposite direction. http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/Newt.html

Define your experiments...

Print nozzles with different size openings, different lengths, different infill ratios (and therefore weights), put them on balloons, inflate, release, observe, record data, analyze and infer. You might include a precision scale to weigh the balloons and nozzles.

How does the time aloft vary with the size of the nozzle opening?

Which nozzles have the most stable flight?

Which nozzles achieve the maximum altitude?

Why?

2 parts

Ballons - I've been using the 12" latex variety so far, but I saw some 24" balloons at the party store that were tempting to try, if their opening is too different from the 12" we can just print new nozzles to fit.

3d printed nozzles in various sizes. Change the opening, change the length, change the infill ratio (weight). You probably want some kind of labeling scheme to tell them apart - this could be something like each type of nozzle printed in a different color plastic, or mark on a light color plastic with a sharpie, or just keep them in separate bins and keep measuring tools handy for when they get confused.

• Fluid dynamics
  • Dynamic stability
  • Balloon blowing
  • Measurement
  • Data recording
  • Data analysis

remixed_from.title: Shake Table for Engineer's Week Project

description.text:
Mark V upgrade 3/9/18.

The application: Students build towers from spaghetti and marshmallows then see if they can take the seismic forces from this little table. Upper table oscillates on 4 parallelogram arms, two of which are driven by a cranks. Cranks in turn are attached to a drive shaft with a 1/4" hexagon allowing it to be rotated by an electric screwdriver or cordless drill.

This upgrade adds proper bearings as plastic on plastic galls at high speed; replaces pivot pins with brass ones removing failures of locking pins and improves the rotating lock pins that hold the platen in place without the need for binder clips. I have added an exploded diagram to explain the layout and ease assembly. Bearings are readily available on line and not too expensive. Also dwgs of the brass parts are included. if you don't have a lathe to make these on you can use the dwgs to make the parts in plastic, just make plenty of spares for when they break.

You will probably have to run a 17/64" drill through most of the holes to open them up for the pivot pins - especially where the part lies on the 3D printer table.
You will need to superglue the brass parts together once assembled, making sure you don't get any on the plastic parts. Also superglue the boss and lock tabs together once fitted taking care not to get any between the boss and the top plate. After you have assembled the needle bearings, inner drive arms and drive shaft you can fit them onto the baseplate and fix them in place with the plumber blocks, again by carefully applying some superglue on the upward projections on the baseplate.

Parts list on exploded diagram says how many parts you need for each shaker table, however you need to add extra platens - suggest # of students /6 - this allows towers to be built off the shake table and loaded on for testing

I also downloaded the monkey at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1185699/#files to add to the fun - the kids have to make a tower that keeps the monkey from falling off it when shaken. Monkey can be scaled to about 50-60% for this application.

Video of demonstration on an older variant of the design at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=szCDBG8XrE0&spfreload=10

title: Sonoff Basic Decora Cover (Capacitive Touch Version)

description.text:
This is my remix of the cover for mmasson's sonoff enclosure (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2804973). I've modded this to house an httm capacitive touch switch (https://www.aliexpress.com/item/5-pcs-Blue-Color-HTTM-Series-Capacitive-Touch-Switch-Button-Module-New/32471771544.html). I've also inset a power icon so it glows when the sonoff is turned off to be found easily. The touch switch is wired into GPIO14, and the input is tied to ground using a 10K resistor.

For this particular switch I'm using Tasmota firmware and GPIO14 set to Switch4 - Switchmode 4

YouTube video of the switch in action: https://youtu.be/Nk1kS23YD8s

Note: these capacitive touch switches come in latching mode, which is what I'm currently using them in. You can solder a resistor which will convert it to a momentary switch, I think I'm going to end up going this route so the LED is constantly on. The downfall of having the latching switch is if you turn the switch off remotely, the LED on the switch will stay in an off state and I don't believe there is a way to change the design. Changing it to a momentary switch will ensure the LED stays on so you can see it in the dark when turned off remotely. I will post pictures once I do this modification.

Update: So I soldered a resistor to one of the httm switches to give the momentary mode a try, unfortunately the switch defaults to an OFF state and goes high with the LED ON while touching, this won't work for me. Keeping them in latching mode for now.

title: Monoprice Select Mini X-Axis Belt Tensioner cap
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a replacement end cap for the x-axis rods on the Monoprice Select Mini. This cap is longer than original, and provides a slot for the pulley assembly to slide in, so that you can tension the belt without using the spring tensioners, or other tensioners that ride on the belt.

The tension is adjusted by tightening the knob, which pulls the screw and moves the pulley assembly within the cap.

Also, the internal dimensions are tighter than the factory cap, so that the pulley cannot rotate out of alignment.

This cap doesn't work with the sheet metal x-axis cover -- but who really wants that thing anyway?

You will need:

  • an M3 screw, of about 25mm length (longer will work too)

description.text:
A mouthpiece getting stuck is SOOOO annoying. Unfortunately, they cost $40 on Amazon! In preparation for the marching band season, I decided to make a cheap, 3D printed mouthpiece remover. This was made to work on trumpet mouthpiece, however it should work on most other small mouthpieces like french horn, mellophone, cornet, and fugal. In total this project cost $7 to make and 30 minutes to assemble. Total printing time was 5 hours at .1 mm with the Tevo Tornado.

How to remove a mouthpiece:

  1. loosen the crown bolts at the bottom of the mouthpiece remover until the sliders can slide.
  2. move the two sliders away from each other to make room form the mouthpiece.
  3. turn the bottom wing nut on the threaded rod clockwise (bottom point of view), and alternate this process on both sides until the mouthpiece can be placed in with the sliders above the lip were the mouthpiece connects to the lead pipe.
  4. move the sliders inwards to secure the base of the mouthpiece. Tighten the two crown bolts to lock the sliders in places.
  5. alternate turning the top two wing nuts clockwise (top point of view) until the mouthpiece pops out. WARNING: They can really pop out quite aggressively, I'm not responsible if any mouthpiece gets dents by falling on the floor.
    Here's a video of me using it:
    https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AeP1htOAiFo

Materials:

All the supplies were found at Home Depot.
1/4 in threaded rod
1/4 in - 20 nylon lock nut (2 needed)
1/4 in - 20 nut (2 needed)
1/4 in - 20 wing nuts (4 needed)
number 8-32 x 3/8" wing/crown screw (2 needed)
number 8 metal washer (2 needed)

Assembly:

Print all the parts out (no supports required!)
Cut the threaded rod to an appropriate length (mine were 3.75 in long)
Insert the threaded rod into both the threaded holes in the top section of the mouthpiece remover to break away any lose plastic/defects in the print. Remove the rod afterwards.
At one end of each of the threaded rod, put on a lock nut. They can be twisted on part of the way by hand, but then you need to use a wrench and pliers to twist the nut until the end is flush with the rod.
Insert one of the rods with the nut into the bottom of the build. Then, put on that sides slider and hold it in with it's corresponding crown bolt and washer.
Insert the rod into the top section of the build. Use the wing nuts and regular nuts to help twist it on (see picture for nut setup)
Insert the other rod into the other whole, again put on its wing nuts and nut to twist it in.
Put on the other slider and its crown bolt and washer and you're done!

I designed this using fusion 360 and by looking at pictures of existing mouthpiece removers. If you enjoyed this project, a tip/like would be very much appreciated!

description.text:
Originally produced by Games Workshop for their 6mm scale table top wargame, Epic 40,000 (and its predecessors and successors). They have since abandoned all support for their game, so I modeled this in Autodesk Inventor for any avid wargamers.

Modelled on the FW Warhound so will stand around 38mm tall. According to Warhammer Wiki, a 1:300 true-scale Warhound should be around 46mm tall, so if you're a stickler for scale, rescale all components by 123%.

Epic is being re-released as Adeptus Titanicus some time in the near future, though reports indicate it will initially be titans only. Apparently it will be 8mm scale instead of 6mm, so I suggest that anyone wanting to print this for AT gaming should upscale it by 163%.

title: Yet another TUSH Remix (Mechanical Tolerance Fixes)

description.text:
I had trouble getting the original TUSH to fit the bearings I had - they were exactly 8mm ID, it has zero built in mechanical tolerances, and any oversize error like I've been getting on my printer can stop it fitting. I've seen others reduce the peg diameter, but wanted a more flexible solution that doesn't have to be adjusted based on the exact degree my printer is oversizing them.

Rather than plain round pegs, this version has a tapered peg with an X slot cut out of it (starts narrower at the base, works slowly out to 8mm, then tapers back in right at the top). This is designed to flex slightly when a bearing is pushed on to it, and then snap on and hold on to the inside of the bearing. While the slot won't print perfectly at this scale on my printer, it will still give inwards to tolerate a range of levels of overprinting.

I also cut some circles out of it like I've seen other remixes doing, as this allows us to reduce plastic and print time, while providing better structural strength than hollowing it and using infill.

description.text:
Here's a complete replacement carriage to mount an E3Dv6 Volcano on to a Monoprice Select Mini. This part features:

  • Integrated 40mm fan shroud -- provides cooling for the heat sink and also has ducts to cool the print. It's all one unit, so it's very solid and consistent.

  • Integrated belt mounting notch -- doesn't require any extra pieces or hardware.

  • Little to no offset from the factory nozzle position -- doesn't require a z-spacer, and the zero position on the Y axis won't put the nozzle off the front of the print bed.

  • Super easy printing. You should be able to print this without supports, all in one print. (See example print-bed layout in the photos.)

  • 3 piece design, so you can print them in different materials if you want. For example, you could print the carriage in PLA, and print the pieces that contact the E3Dv6 in PETG. I printed everything in PLA and I haven't seen any issues.

In order to use this, you will need:

  1. E3Dv6 Volcano (or clone)

  2. 40mm fan. For mounting the fan, clearance for screws is a bit tight -- I use zip ties, which work great.

  3. Some sort of hardware to hold it together. #6-32 x 2" screws fit best. If you want to use metric, M3 x 50mm screws also fit. M4 screws might also work, but you'll probably have to thread them into the plastic. I have done a few prints with only zip ties (very tight zip ties) holding the whole thing together, and it actually worked just fine that way too.

Also you'll need to reuse the linear bearings out of your current carriage. If they're tight, don't hammer them in, press them in.

Kawai Tsugite is a Japanese joint that can be assembled three different ways - one in a straight line, two at right angles.
The way to build a wooden one is pretty well described in this page: https://www.ethan-brammeier.com/kawai-tsugite-joint

My idea was to recreate under OpenScad what a good Japanese woodworker would do:

  • cut a pyramid corner
  • remove 3 prismatic bits
  • give some play for a smooth assembly.

If you open the scad file, you'll see how easy this translates into OpensScad.

As we're under OpenScad, the thing can be easily customized with the customizer: just click on "open in Customizer" button...

All the pieces of the puzzle are the same.

  • You may start printing 2 of them and play with the Kawai joint which is already quite fun!
  • If you print 4 of them you get quite a challenging puzzle, the major difficulty being to take it apart. To do so, you'll have to diagonaly slide mm per mm each four blocks to expand the surface occupied by the puzzle (see the partly assembled picture)
  • Now, if you print 8 of them, you'll get all the elements to make a perfect cube.

Have fun !

description.text:
I made this miniature holder to help me with painting 40k figures. There are some parts of some miniatures that require lots of handling in awkward positions (upside down, etc.).

There are some good painting aides available here. But I decided to make one that can easily accommodate anything with a base from 25 to 40 mm, and be comfortable to hold. Although overcomplicated for a painting aide, it work's well for my needs.

Can also be used for display purposes.

ABS parts (or pla)
3x 2.5mm electric cable termination jacks (as cam followers)
1x small rubber band
(optional) 3x M3x5mm sunken head screws.
(optional) Grease (appropriate to the filament you use like PTFE Grease)

  • the pitch on the cam shafts is non linear to allow grater force and control on the ends of travel.
  • the rotation for the cam disk/axel is clockwise (to open). Although it feels "backswords" it is done so you won't unscrew the base/handle while opening the sliders.

  • do not use for spray paint !!!

  • the Emperor protects !!

Printer:

Kossel mini

No

No

Resolution:

0.2 and 0.1

Infill:

Notes:

Base_1.STL is the only one part requires support when printing. Also I recommand using a 1 layer skirt for the small parts and the tall ones. I suggest printing the threaded section of each threaded part with 0.1 layer height (if your slicer allow for layer height change)

step1

Print all the parts in this orientation. Careful with the very small ones and the tall ones. I recommand a slow speed. (you'll need 3 of Slider_25_40mm.STL )

Concerning the top cover. I uploaded 2 versions. One with holes for screws and one without holes but with pins instead. You'll have to print only one of this two (top_with_pins.STL or top_with_holes.STL)

step2

Thread the handle in the base of the painting aide (no glue necessary)

step3

Snap together the axel and cam disk (you can glue this if needed)

step4

Slide the axel though the handle (you can grease the bottom of the cam disk and the inside of the 3 cam tracks)

step5

Snap the axel base in it's place (this can be glued BUT do this after you are sure you don't have to disassemble it later)

step6

After cleaning the supports of the Base_1.STL part, carefully thread this part in the Base_2.STL thread (this thread is very fine dew to size restriction. if not printed at 0.1 it may not work well) - I will address this later iterations...

Also, you can carefully snap this parts together if printed in ABS (more flexible then pla).

step7 (optional. your printer may print this perfectly)

On a piece of fine sandpaper, grind the edges of the three Slider_25_40mm.STL parts. They must be smooth to the touch and fit snugly, while easily sliding in their grooves (in the top of the Base_1.STL part)

step8

Cut the plastic part of the 2.5mm electric cable termination and put the remaining metal part through the Slider_25_40mm.STL parts. You can hold them in place with a small drop of superglue.

(you can use any other metal pin here if it fits the hole/cam track)

step9

Place the 3 sliders in their groove while carefully putting the metal pins in the cam disk below.

Put the rubber band in it's groove like in the image below. Chose a rubber band that fits with very little tension with the sliders in their closed position !!!

step10

Put the top_with_holes.STL part on the holder and screw in the 3 screws. Alternatively, you can snap in place the top_with_pins.STL part.

If you decide to put the top_with_pins.STL it may be necessary to trim some excess plastic of the pins (depending on your printer retraction setting) - After you test and are satisfied with the mechanical aspect (ease of sliding, force of the rubber band, etc) you can glue the top_with_pins.STL part. I didn't glue mine and it staid in place just fine with only the pins.

final words

When all is done, you should easily hold a miniature by it's base in any position. The tension provided by the rubber band should be enough.

  • the Emperor protects !!

description.text:
Not sure why everyone uses axial fans for cooling the extruded filament.
A radial blower and a flex pipe seem much more appropriate for this task. With the flex pipe the stream of cool air can be precisely directed at the tip of the hotend and a small ( 12V, 125mA ) radial blower creates enough pressure to push the air through the flex pipe. First tests show very promising results. Now I can maintain 245°C on the hotend with full cooling ( without the head wrapped in kapton tape ). Also the extruded filament seems to be cooled much better than with the standard 40mm fan+nozzle which I used before.

This thing is just the adapter that connects the blower, the printer frame and the first segment of the flex pipe. For the flex pipe and nozzle please refer to http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:43272 and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:63366 The blower is fixed in place with glue ( 2K epoxy ). For the flex pipe I tried to integrate the ball joint into this design but I came to the conclusion that it is easier to also use glue to attach the first segment of the flex pipe.

Problem

As a home brewer I wanted to use individual bottle cap designs instead of labels to differentiate my batches, because removing labels is always a pain. At first I thought of creating stamps for applying the design to the caps, but it didn't work out, because it was difficult to align and resulted in blurry prints. As I don't have labels, bottle caps have to be as pretty as possible ...

Solution

Laser engraving the designs turned out to be the solution for me. Although monochromatic, the results look great on colored bottle caps. To engrave many bottle caps at once I designed this customizable jig.

Printing

You may have to adjust values a bit (use the customizer or open in OpenSCAD) to ensure a tight fit of the bottle caps on the jig. Print just one holder to try, adjust values and repeat. Laser engraving

I use a Fabtotum 3d printer with laser head to engrave my designs. The jig has small center markings on each holder which can be used to align it to the laser engraver. I painted them black for better contrast.

title: Ideal RPG/Wargame Dice (D12 on D60)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Ideal RPG/Wargame Dice

Each time you need to roll "one more than before", it becomes more difficult by the same factor (133%), approximately.

Great for sensible difficulty increases in RPGs and Wargames that use a lot of Die Modifiers (+/- DMs)

Can be used in game design to eliminate complicated rules, extra tables, and mental arithmetics. Also great as a drop-in replacement for a D12 or 2D6.

Includes OpenSCAD source files in case you'd like to modify the design.

Based on

  • pmoews' D60: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1045263
  • my own intuitive D20: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2811944

Probabilities

The Ideal Dice feature the following distribution:

  • 1: 15x
  • 2: 11x
  • 3: 9x
  • 4: 6x
  • 5: 5x
  • 6: 3x
  • 7: 3x
  • 8: 2x
  • 9: 2x
  • 10: 1x
  • 11: 1x
  • 12: 2x

The chances of achieving a certain number or higher are:

  • 1: 100% :-)
  • 2: 75%
  • 3: 57%
  • 4: 42%
  • 5: 32%
  • 6: 23%
  • 7: 18%
  • 8: 13%
  • 9: 10%
  • 10: 6.7%
  • 11: 5.0%
  • 12: 3.3%

The chances of success for each increase of +1 are reduced to the following percentage of the unmodified chances:

1 + 1: 75%
2 + 1: 76%
3 + 1: 74%
4 + 1: 76%
5 + 1: 74%
6 + 1: 79%
7 + 1: 73%
8 + 1: 75%
9 + 1: 67%
10 + 1: 75%
*11 + 1: 67%

So the die is not perfect, due to only having a finite number of faces, but I think it's pretty good :-)

History

I came up with this die out of frustration with convention die roll modification systems back in the late 1980s, calling it the "logarithmic die". Attempts to build such a die by modifying existing D20 dies resulted in ugly, stickered, poorly-rolling creations so that I gave up on the concept.

My hopes that someone else would have the same idea and come up with a nice mass-produced die of this type unfortunately never materialized.

With the advent 3D printing, it suddenly became easy to have good-looking and accurate dice printed, so I designed D20 dice in FreeCAD, which came out great.

As the D20 only delivers numbers from 1 to 7, I kept looking for a bigger die that would give a greater range of numbers, and when I found pmoews' D60, that was just perfect for the purpose as it can be used to give a range of 1 to 12, just what many games need.

So, here's the ideal logarithmic D60 for you! :-)

All this started out as a question that was posted on the EndlessSphere E-Bike forum regarding the practicality of printing modules on on a 3D printer that could be assembled together to form a battery frame for an 18650 battery pack. I tried a small hex unit for a single 18650 cell with dovetails and came to the conclusion that it was more trouble than it was worth. Thus I decided to try larger modules.

Most e-bike batteries are in the range of 36 to 60 volts which is 10 to 15 cells in series. They are also commonly 4 or 5 cells in parallel. The largest section size that I can print on my Creality Ender-2 is 5 by 5 and I have to lie to Cura a bit to accomplish that. The Ender-2 has a bit larger print bed than some other 3D printers in the same price and size range. Thus I decided to create the modules in both four and five parallel sections. A 36 volt battery only requires two FourByFive or FiveByFive sections to assemble a frame for each side of the battery pack. For more cells in series a center section is needed. Those of you that have the luxury of larger printbeds can join the sections in your slicer program to produce the frame as a single print.

The parameters I used for the design were:
Height = 8.0 mm
Cell Hole Diameter = 18.60 mm
Cell Center to Center Distance = 20.00 mm
Mounting Hole Diameter = 3.0 mm
Mounting Hole Edge to Center Distance = 3.5 mm
Mounting Hole Center to Center Distance = 20, 40 or 60 mm
Chamfer Distance = 0.80 mm

In order to determine the optimum cell hole diameter I designed and printed a gauge in ABS. I then test fit several cells into the gauge to determine the best fit. The size I chose was for a Samsung INR18650-25R that actually measures 18.30mm in diameter. There is some variance between the design size hole and the finished print. Some other cells such as UltraFire will be a bit sloppy.

As I chose to print these in ABS I had some problems with bed adhesion and warping. Thus I used a large brim and a generous amount of hair spray. To aid in cleanly removing the brim I incorporated 0.80 mm chamfers along the lower edges of the sections.

The Tabs and Sockets used to join the sections together are intended to be used during the process of solvent adhesive bonding of the sections. I do not believe that they provide adequate strength for an assembled battery pack on their own. I also encourage allowing sufficient time for the curing process. For bonding I recommend one of the following:

SCIGRIP #16 Acrylic Cement
IPS Weld-On #4 Acrylic Adhesive
IPS Weld-On #3  Acrylic Adhesive
Testors Model Comment #3509C
Methylene Chloride (99% pure)
Acetone (99% pure) … nail polish remover

I used SCIGRIP for testing because it is what I happened to have on hand. I suspect that IPS Weld-On #3 would produce the best bond. I find that XXXByOne sections are a bit flimsy however they may be adequate in an assembled frame.

The 3mm holes along the sides were the last feature that I added after I discovered that one could acquire M3 Hex Socket head screws in 75 and 90 mm lengths. I find that I need to ream the small holes with a appropriate twist drill bit depending on if they are to be used as a clear through hole or threaded. There are other methods that can be used to secure the two sides but this alternative is provided because it was convenient to do so.

All the test prints were made using “Paramount 3D ABS (PANTONE Battleship Gray 431C) 1.75mm Filament” with a extrusion temperature of 225 degrees and a bed temperature of 100 degrees in 0.20mm layers. I also had the extrusion factor down to 0.95 to maintain detail for for the tabs and sockets. There was zero fill with 8 to 10 walls to produce a solid print.

Note that the left and right sides are opposite hand but the center sections (i.e. XXX-L-H and XXX-R-H) are interchangeable.

For those that have a CAD system capable correct loading a 3D DWG/DXF file with AICS solids I have also included the original CAD DXF files. All design work was done with BrisCAD 18.x running on a Linux Mint 18.3 operating system.

The mission was a four-hour, two-orbit test of the Orion crew module featuring a high apogee on the second orbit and concluding with a high-energy reentry at around 20,000 miles per hour (32,000 km/h; 8,900 m/s).[3]This mission design corresponds to the Apollo 4 mission of 1967, which validated the Apollo flight control system and heat shield at re-entry conditions planned for the return from lunar missions. The flight was intended to test various Orion systems, including separation events, avionics, heat shielding, parachutes, and recovery operations prior to its debut launch aboard the Space Launch System.

I wanted more light but 3 LEDs pull too much current for a CR2032 cell. I therefore designed this base to run from a 2 AA battery pack.on a short lead;

How to wire this up (a little fiddly)

  • Bend the 2 outer LED leads furthest from the power input in to the channel, trim the leads so they only just reach the centre LED, an solder them to centre LED

  • Solder an insualted power lead under those leads, pushing it in to the left channel cut-out so it will dip under the other channel

  • Repeat the first 2 steps for the other leads using the channel nearest the power input

  • Trim the connections

  • I fit a rubber or felt cover on the base to prevent short circuits and damage to the surfaces it's placed on.

I use 5 mm slow colour-changing RGB LEDs but almost any type and size can be used. These LEDs are very bright but have a narrow beam angle so made a sinple diffuser to drop over the 5mm LEDs (link)

I found if I held the compressor in the air while it was running, it was much quieter outside of the room I was in as the vibrations were dampened. So I created the squash ball feet that dampen the vibration to be just about the same as holding the compressor in the air.

To install, take off each rubber foot by unscrewing the screw holding them in the center. Watch out for the small washer as it tends to fall out especially later so I recommend taking it out and setting it aside. Push the original rubber foot through this printed foot. Then use the original screw and washer to put it back on the compressor. Then insert the squash ball. No additional parts are needed besides the 3d printed feet.

description.text:
After making the gazillionth box from scratch for my newest electronic module, I decided to parametrize (?) my latest design and save time in the future.

THERE YOU GO, YOU'RE WELCOME!

Everything is derived from the distance between the PCB mounting holes in X and in Y. So unfortunately this design relies on a rectangular 4x screw mounting pattern, but should be easy to mod if you need something different.

So the way it works is: in Fusion360 Modelling mode > Modify > Change Parameters you input the mounting hole distances and enter the margins you want around your PCB. Everything resizes like magic :)

Check out my instagram to see it in action and the customisable parameters.

This is my design of a spool holder holder. Weird, I know. It's basically a stand for 8mm rod type roller spool holders and is simply a drop in holder. There are two sizes:

STANDARD

Spool stand

No post printing actions necessary.

Assembly

For the spool rollers (see links above) you'll need:
-8mm threaded rod (~140 mm)
-M8 nuts
-608 bearings
-Loctite

Press in the bearings on both sides. Cut the 8mm rod to length and thread on the M8 nuts so that both sides stick out evenly. Use Loctite!

The spool stand is designed for usage of standard M8 nuts, not the security type. The 8mm rod will drop right into the slots.

I used Fusion360. I started with a sketch of a 10mm base and a circle (bearing) on top. For the outlines I used splines. Then I pulled the whole thing out with Q to the outside dimensions. Then I created a sketch at the bottom with a rectangle of the inside dimensions and cut with Q. Then I went crazy with the fillets... ;-)

These are Loonie shaped shopping cart tokens - 11-sided Reuleaux polygons. The lithophane is inside the token, so it's hidden unless looking at it with a bright background light.

There are several models included, each with a different picture for the lithophane. Also included is a solid token with no lithophane. The OpenSCAD file used to generate them is included so you can make them with your own pictures or adapt the model for coin tokens in your own country. The picture should be in greyscale with high contrast to get the best effect and with some pixels completely black so that the layer on top of the picture has some places to print directly on top of. The lithophane is only 1.2 mm in height, so don't expect a lot of detail.

The tokens with lithophanes must be printed with 100% infill so that the lithophane prints correctly. You'll need to print with a light colored filament to allow the light to pass through.

The dome part I did design first as one single part, saved a copy of it, and then cut the lower part of the dome first. Same I did with the upper part of the dome and then made the finishing of these two parts, to get a cover that can be taken away.

title: Tiered Wall Hanging Planter

description.text:
This is a tiered hanging wall planter that can be hung inside or outside. It is designed so that you hang each planter box above the other and can create longer rows by placing them side-by-side. There are 2 types of planter boxes. One with holes in the bottom and the other without. This allows you to hang the planter boxes above each other with only the bottom one not having any holes. When you water it, the water will continue to drip down through each successive planter box where it can’t go any further when it hits the bottom one which has no holes. Make sure the boxes are planted with good drainage and a course material in the bottom of the planter to allow for drainage.
If you plan on using this outside, you can have all the planter boxes with holes and just let drain to the ground.

Mounting:
To mount on the wall or a wood backer, attach the hanger strip with small recessed screws. Then just slide the back of the planter box on-top of the hanger strip.
If mounting outside you can hang a piece of welded wire mesh (usually 2”x4” squares) and just hang the boxes off the wire row. Since the mesh squares are usually smaller than the width of the planter box, you will need to just align the notch on the back of the planer to the vertical wire of the mesh and straddle two boxes.

Printing With and Without Supports:
Because I don’t like print with supports, I designed a version of the 2 planters to have internal braces that extend across the inside bottom of the planter boxes. This allows me to get a pretty good bottom without using supports. So, there are 4 planter box STL files.

  • Planter without holes – Needs supports
  • Planter with holes – Needs supports
  • Planter without holes – Shouldn’t need supports
  • Planter with holes – Shouldn’t need supports

This is a remix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1503525 I think this was a great build to start with, so I only did a few tweaks.

1.) Scope Modifications - Hollowed it out so that you can see through it and added a set of cross hairs. I also modified the two long pieces so that they can "snap" together instead of having a flat junction.

2.) Muzzle Modification - The muzzle did not have a matching diameter to the barrel, so I added a fill piece to make them fit together nicely.

3.) Scope Clamp Modification - I had to do quite a bit of filing on the scope clamps to properly fit around the scope. So I modified the inner diameter to allow the pieces to fit together without any post build modifications.

4.) I broke up some of the build files that had multiple pieces into single ones. My printer puts out better prints if I keep things towards the center of the print bed.

For the final paint I did a chrome base coat with a light black for the top coat. Purposely letting it get too thin in places. I think it turned out well for a weathered metal look.

description.text:
Luftdata?

I'm part of a Swedish Citizen science projekt luftdata.se measuring
air particles using a sds011 sensor. It's a branch from the original german projekt luftdaten.info where you can read build instructions etc in English.

(You can of course also use the model to measure to other things then particle measurements, I've printed one identical where I have a BME280, BH1750 and a external tipping bucket for rain thus making my own weather station!)

You can see a live map of all the particle readings here


The original case is made of 2 pieces 87° sewer pipes and that's a cheap and sturdy solution but I wanted something that looked a bit better on my wall so I designed this stevensson screen sensor holder. It fits the sds011 sensor and a DHT22/BME280 besides the mandatory nodeMCU/WemosD1

Stevensson what?

A Stevenson screen or instrument shelter is a shelter or an enclosure to shield meteorological instruments against precipitation and direct heat radiation from outside sources, while still allowing air to circulate freely around them. You have probably seen some around in the world without thinking about it but it was first designed at the end of 1880!

Parts

It's enough with 2 bolts to keep it together but if you want to be on the really super safe side it's designed to use 4 bolts.
I recommend that you get stainless bolts and nuts since it'll be placed outside.

Printed parts

  • 6x middle part
  • 1x wall bottom part
  • 1x top part
  • 1x sds011 holder

Bought parts

  • 2-4x M8x100mm bolts
  • 2-4x M8 nuts
  • 2x wood screws

Printer:

RepRapPro Mono Mendel

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Notes:

I used a rather high percentage (60%) for the bottom part since it needs to carry the rest of the parts and keeping it stable.
The other parts are just printed with 25% infill since that's as low as I usually go.

Don't use any support, if you turn all the parts in the right direction it won't be needed.

Step 1: Clean and Count

Clean all parts from any stringing and make sure you have printed the right number of all the parts.

Step 2: Build the sensor

Ah yeah, you need a sensor to so head over to luftdata.se for the Swedish instructions or luftdaten.info for the English instructions.
They also have instructions in a couple of other languages on their site.

Step 3: Attach sensors to the sds011 holder

Use cable ties to attach the sds011, DHT22/BME280 and NodeMCU/Wemos to the inside of the mesh part. Try to get the ties situated in 4 different corners for making the insertion easier.

Step 4: Fit the nuts to the top part

My suggstion is to heat up the nuts some and melt them down into the correct places in the top part making sure to get them as straight as possible.

Step 5: Attach the bottom part to a wall

Use 2 wood screws (max 3,5mm diameter) to fasten the bottom part to a wall, remember that you need to have access to a USB cable to power the unit.

Step 6: Stack the parts

This part can be a bit tricky so you might want to get help from someone to hand you the pieces.
Start with one bolt from the bottom and while holding it with one hand thread the other 6 middle parts onto it. After that insert the mesh holder for the sensor and finally put on the top part and attach the bolt to the nut.
Before you tighten it up to much insert the other bolt(s) and make sure that you manage to line up the holes correctly.
